  <p>When you’re making a Medicare decision, it’s fair to ask: <em>who am I trusting?</em> Here’s what stands behind the guidance on this site — the licensing, the annual certifications, and the compliance rules a Medicare agent has to follow.</p>

  <h2>Licensed &amp; Local</h2>
  <p><strong>Rocco DeLuca</strong> is a licensed insurance agent in Utah, focused on Medicare for <a href="medicare-plans-vernal-utah.html">Vernal</a> and the surrounding Uintah Basin. He operates from {BUSINESS.containedInPlace} at {BUSINESS.street} in {BUSINESS.city}, and helps neighbors across the Basin in person, by phone, and by video. <a href="about.html">Meet Rocco →</a></p>

  <h2>Annual Certifications</h2>
  <p>Offering Medicare Advantage and Part D plans isn’t something an agent can do casually. <strong>Every year</strong>, before he can discuss or enroll you in a plan, a Medicare agent must:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Pass the <strong>AHIP Medicare certification</strong> — the industry-standard annual exam on Medicare rules and ethical marketing.</li>
    <li>Complete <strong>each carrier’s product certification</strong> for the plans they offer — separately, every year.</li>
    <li>Stay current on that year’s CMS marketing rules and plan changes.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>That’s why working with a certified local agent means the plan details you hear are current for the year you’re enrolling.</p>

  <h2>Compliance You Can Count On</h2>
  <p>We follow the CMS rules that protect Medicare beneficiaries: <em>we do not offer every plan available in your area</em>, we don’t pressure or cold-call, and we’re clear that we’re <strong>not connected with or endorsed by the U.S. government or the federal Medicare program</strong>. For every plan in your area, you can always contact <a href="https://www.medicare.gov" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Medicare.gov</a> or 1-800-MEDICARE (TTY: 711). How we research and review our content is spelled out in our <a href="editorial-policy.html">editorial policy</a>.</p>

